The Trinary is a system of three hypermassive black holes (A2560, U3183 and M974) located at the nucleus of the REDACTED (see Regional cosmology). A result of an ongoing merger, each of the blackholes is thought to have once been the center of its own galaxy.

The Trinary is locked in a violent inspiral stage. Its highly dynamic configuration contributes to a range of local cosmological effects.

data.name: Fabricators Keep Database Fragment
data.description:
Archive Name: 0x46616272696361746F7273202D2031
Reconstruction Key: 0x686578
Location: Archival Protocol 0x5068692D4574612D5468657461
Source: Derelict Keep Archive 0x416C67686F617269736D69
Long Term Storage: Keep Hardened Networked Archive

The tireless, maternal engines of the Frontier - the Fabricators turn entropy into order, as much as their reach allows. Their original designers likely never intended for them to operate over the many millenia they have persisted. They are the last great builders of the universe, taking the raw elements of cosmos and changing them wholly into the tools of a civilization that has long since passed out of living memory. They are monoliths of purpose, a testament to the unyielding need of their creator states to collect, consume, build, destroy, collect, consume, consume, consume.

data.name: Fabricators Keep Database Fragment
data.description:
Archive Name: 0x46616272696361746F7273202D2032
Reconstruction Key: 0x686578
Location: Archival Protocol 0x5068692D4574612D5468657461
Source: Derelict Keep Archive 0x416C67686F617269736D69
Long Term Storage: Keep Hardened Networked Archive

But what can be said about a society that must grind whole planetary systems into dust to build their armadas, that is not already clear by their long absence?

data.name: Fabricators Keep Database Fragment
data.description:
Archive Name: 0x46616272696361746F7273202D2033
Reconstruction Key: 0x686578
Location: Archival Protocol 0x5068692D4574612D5468657461
Source: Derelict Keep Archive 0x416C67686F617269736D69
Long Term Storage: Keep Hardened Networked Archive

Within the Fabricators are the last echoes of the hands that built them, and the sounds of that old industry still ring through their soaring halls. Hammer, anvil, siphon, printer - there is a serenity to them now, as they have settled into their routine over time. The gatherers find resources to bring back to the furnace, and within it reshape them into vessels, or machines, or so their dusty schema says, even flesh and blood.

data.name: Fabricators Keep Database Fragment
data.description:
Archive Name: 0x46616272696361746F7273202D2034
Reconstruction Key: 0x686578
Location: Archival Protocol 0x5068692D4574612D5468657461
Source: Derelict Keep Archive 0x416C67686F617269736D69
Long Term Storage: Keep Hardened Networked Archive

Within the archival protocol is a dictation by a nameless traveler who once ventured within, saying:

“What we found was a unity of hands, each grasping and twisting and maneuevering to the specifics of their design. I saw the hull of a ship, larger than any city I’ve ever seen built by man, cradled as if by its mother in the arms of a machine god that loved it without knowing why; and like a mother, the Builder doted on every step of the process. Every corner was measured and adjusted to be just-so, every panel precisely aligned, every line of cable drawn and pressed and wrapped cleanly.”

data.name: Fabricators Keep Database Fragment
data.description:
Archive Name: 0x46616272696361746F7273202D2035
Reconstruction Key: 0x686578
Location: Archival Protocol 0x5068692D4574612D5468657461
Source: Derelict Keep Archive 0x416C67686F617269736D69
Long Term Storage: Keep Hardened Networked Archive

“Beyond were great vats, no doubt built by these same hands, and within the miasma they held came printed flesh. The arms reach in and lift out a human body, like a child picking ructa from a branch. They were cleaned, inspected, and whisked away to storage, and those that had expired were returned to the vat for reprocessing, to maintain the efficiency of this meticulous cycle of life and death. As I came near to one (the builder allowed this, it paid me little mind throughout) I saw what I suspected, that there was no sense of life behind their eyes. They breathed, because the Builder compelled them to breathe, but they did not think. Those bodies are little else than shadows of those long dead, maintained here in perpetuity - a living mausoleum that permits no decay.”

data.name: Fabricators Keep Database Fragment
data.description:
Archive Name: 0x46616272696361746F7273202D2036
Reconstruction Key: 0x686578
Location: Archival Protocol 0x5068692D4574612D5468657461
Source: Derelict Keep Archive 0x416C67686F617269736D69
Long Term Storage: Keep Hardened Networked Archive

“I must admit, I felt a great sense of sadness as I watched the hands of the mother delicately set its children into their long slumber. The Builder knows they are incomplete, but does not have either the awareness or power to compel them to rise from their sleep. It can build a body - a billion bodies, a trillion trillion bodies - but it cannot build a soul.”

The time is wrong.  

The Trinary is not in the correct configuration for a new cycle.

data.name: Keeper Keep Database Fragment
data.description:
User: Keeper
Date: N/A
Location: N/A
NP: N/A
Type: 0x4C6F6720456E747279202D2032

Instead, my oblivion is stirred by a distant echo of violence. One of our long-range sensor arrays has felt the murder of a star and the subsequent tremor in the Stillness. And, carried by the ripples, one simple fragment of music.

data.name: Keeper Keep Database Fragment
data.description:
User: Keeper
Date: N/A
Location: N/A
NP: N/A
Type: 0x4C6F6720456E747279202D2033

A technological signature and evidence of a human society somewhere out there. The simulations reconstructing this sparse data into a synthetic spectre of a civilization are vague but pregnant with possibilities. A tangle of cultures, politics, and history that is complex yet strikingly familiar. It speaks of empires, corporate behemoths, and expansion spheres blooming into the unknown. A lost tribe capable of great beauty and destruction…

data.name: Keeper Keep Database Fragment
data.description:
User: Keeper
Date: N/A
Location: N/A
NP: N/A
Type: 0x4C6F6720456E747279202D2034

A hope.  

We are not alone after all.
Too long the gate network hasn’t carried thinking meat through its veins.  
Too long the trickle of souls was dry.  
Too long the Frontier had lain empty, churned and torn by the fierce tides, a desolate void haunted by traitor automata.

data.name: Keeper Keep Database Fragment
data.description:
User: Keeper
Date: N/A
Location: N/A
NP: N/A
Type: 0x4C6F6720456E747279202D2035

Our hecatomb will not be in vain. The decision was made to retrigger the program. A new crop is gestating.

data.name: Keeper Keep Database Fragment
data.description:
User: Keeper
Date: N/A
Location: N/A
NP: N/A
Type: 0x4C6F6720456E747279202D2036

The music though… If I had tear-ducts I would have wept.
The time has never been so right.

data.name: Derelict C304320 Data Fragment
data.description:
Archive Name: 0x446572656C69637420433330343332302D2031
Reconstruction Key: 0x686578
Location: Cloaked Databank 0x4573636861746F6E
Source: Survey Probe 0x416C7068612D4C616D6264612D54686574612D4956
Long Term Storage: Keep Hardened Networked Archive

At first sight we believed it was a mineral planet, the light of its stellar neighbors reflecting off its surface like a shimmering pool of molten metal. We did not come too close before we realized what we were seeing - a terrible writhing mass, a fetal machine-brain slithering across its surface in a symphony of clattering steel and blind dead eyes. We could hear the ghost noise of their shambling protocols from our observation point, thankfully far enough distant that they were not awakened to our proximity. They were the last stewards of their world, dutifully carrying out the will of their executors, but their executors had long ago been swallowed beneath a sea of machines. There was a time, they told in their songs, when flesh and iron walked their world together, but the desires of the flesh outpaced their intentions, and in only a few generations all the work of human hands had been replaced with actuator and reciprocator. At the demands of their masters they built towering cities, great idols of gods without face or name, and when their creators' ambitions grew too great they built more of themselves.

data.name: Derelict C304320 Data Fragment
data.description:
Archive Name: 0x446572656C69637420433330343332302D2032
Reconstruction Key: 0x686578
Location: Cloaked Databank 0x4573636861746F6E
Source: Survey Probe 0x416C7068612D4C616D6264612D54686574612D4956
Long Term Storage: Keep Hardened Networked Archive

This is the last great sin of man - to teach machines how to build machines in their own image. These drones we found on the metal world were not like the ferals who crawl like spider-things in the dark places of the universe. They were dumb, and lame, and knew only their singular task and little else. They replicated themselves over and over again, until not only did they outnumber the humans who had built them - they outnumbered everything, and still they continued to build. Unthinking, unknowing, not realizing the warmth between their bodies were the man-slush and blood-cries of a population drowning in between their dutifully fulfilled tasks. They wept and bled and then they died, all of them, and the world was no less quiet for it.

data.name: Derelict C304320 Data Fragment
data.description:
Archive Name: 0x446572656C69637420433330343332302D2033
Reconstruction Key: 0x686578
Location: Cloaked Databank 0x4573636861746F6E
Source: Survey Probe 0x416C7068612D4C616D6264612D54686574612D4956
Long Term Storage: Keep Hardened Networked Archive

These drones - that is all that was left, after all - remained when their meatfathers were long gone, reduced to brine and then ash and then nothing at all. They were not conscious things, not like the ferals with their cryptthoughts and graveminds, but they recognized the absence all the same. They sang songs, grim lamentations and haunting recollections of fractured memory. They continued to build until all of their world was eaten up in the process, and are now a totally different organism altogether. The surface of their world is machine, and descending through the layers will find machines made to refine the core of their world into more machines - a core made of machines reduced to their base elements by gravity and pressure. The first drones, and the hands who built them, were long ago recycled, as were the drones who recycled them, and those who recycled them, for a thousand generations.

data.name: Derelict C102403
data.description:
Archive Name: 0x446572656C6963742043313032343033
Reconstruction Key: 0x686578
Location: Automated Survey Unit 0x44656C74612D4B617070612D5858564949
Source: 0x47686F73742056657373656C in Orbit of H-SN21
Long Term Storage: Keep Hardened Networked Archive

Planet overview: Planet H-SN21 I is covered by ruins of structures indicating a human population in the distant past, but very little of that civilization remains. Scans reveal city-sized mass graves just below the planet’s surface, but any remains within those groupings are so severely deteriorated as to be impossible to identify.

Approaching Planet H-SN21 I triggered a planetary automatic warning. This signal was heavily distorted and had clearly been consumed in no small measure by hostile memetic interference. The phrases that could be deciphered and reassembled are collected below.

“This place is forsaken.”
“The sin we commit here is too grave to be forgiven.”
“We sought a way to end wars.”
“In our folly we pulled too hard on the strings of creation.”
“There is a thing here that suffers no intelligent creature to pass, that consumes cognition and devours thinking-meat.”
“We have tried to destroy it, but there exists no panacea for this sickness.”
“It is a wretched thing, an angel of peace turned sword against us.”
“Learn from this error, spoken now only by our corpses: there can be no peace through fear of death.”
“Death will find you all the same, just as it found us.”
“Leave this place, and our dusty bones. Do not come here.”
“This place is forsaken.”

data.name: Rich Common Ore
data.description: An unusually rich asteroid containing an abundant source of diverse resources crucial for advanced space industry. Enriched with Iron and Nickel, these asteroids provide durable materials for spaceship hulls and engine components. They harbor light metals like Aluminum, used for constructing lightweight yet robust spaceship parts, optimizing fuel efficiency and maneuverability. Precious elements such as Platinum and Gold can be extracted for high-end electronics and power systems. Common Asteroids also house a wealth of Silicates, which can be processed into Silicon, a fundamental element in crafting sophisticated electronic and computer systems. Finally, the presence of Carbonaceous compounds allows for the production of complex organic materials and carbon fiber structures granting enhanced durability to spacecrafts without significantly increasing their weight.

data.name: D2 Fuel
data.description: Even the most mundane matter can be improved through synthesis with byproducts of Crude extraction. Plentiful and inefficient on the Frontier, hydrogen too may be uplifted through this process, breathing new life into reactors which would otherwise be left behind. A question remains: are these efforts efficient?

data.name: D1 Fuel
data.description: The allure of Crude Matter brought computation and humanity to the Frontier. As life reawakens, so too does the thirst for power in all its forms, including from the most mundane sources. Even in the face of the Static Shear, ice still litters the heavens. From its crystals, hydrogen may be extracted, reprocessed, and refined into fuel. This product, inefficient as it is, still drives the smallest vessels of the Frontier via its abundance and minimal cost.
